Although its precise founding date is unknown, it has strong historical ties to {{ill|Kagoshima Jingū|ja|鹿児島神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kagoshima Jingū|qq=}} and {{ill|Kagoshima Shrine (Kagoshima City)|ja|鹿児島神社 (鹿児島市)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kagoshima Shrine (Kagoshima City)|qq=}}. The shrine is thought to have originally worshipped {{ill|Sakurajima|ja|桜島|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sakurajima|qq=}} as its {{ill|shintai|ja|神体|1=Shintai|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/shintai|13=User:Immanuelle/Shintai|qq=}}. Additionally, it maintains a strong connection to {{ill|Tekan Shrine|ja|手貫神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tekan Shrine|qq=}}, another shrine in Tarumizu City known locally as "Kamimiya Shrine."
== Shrine Grounds == A commemorative monument dedicated to {{ill|Setoguchi Tōkichi|ja|瀬戸口藤吉|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Setoguchi Tōkichi|qq=}}, composer of the "{{ill|Gunkan kōshinkyoku|ja|軍艦行進曲|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gunkan kōshinkyoku|qq=}}" (Warship March), is located within the shrine grounds.
